subSubSection.paragraph:
Females. Body and appendages generally transparent, covered with tiny red dots; cornea black, eyestalk transparent, covered with tiny dots; almost all dorsal surface of carapace and dorsal half of its lateral margins covered with uniformly white or white-pinky patch; dorsal surface and dorsal half of pleurae of abdominal somite II with large semicircular white-pinky patch, dorsal surface and dorsal half of pleurae of abdominal somite III with large circular white-pinky patch, dorsal surface of abdominal somite V mostly covered with small semicircular or oval white-pinky spot, sometimes this spot absent, especially in smaller specimens (
Fig. 4
).

Males. General coloration similar to females, with less number of dorsal patches. Body and appendages transparent, covered with tiny red dots; cornea black, eyestalk transparent, covered with tiny dots; dorsal surface of carapace covered with medium uniformly white or white-pinky patch; with uniformly white or white-pinky oval dorsal patch on abdominal somite III (
Fig. 4
).

Differential diagnosis. The new species can be easily differentiated from congeners by specific coloration and occupied host (following
Bruce, 1986
;
Marin, 2012 a
).
